Sensor Fault Detection Using Hierarchical Clustering¶

In production industries engineers and workers rely on sensors to protect and optimize processes more than ever. Sensors taking the role of localised eyes and ears. Therefore sensor fault detecetion attracts considirable attention in digital age.

In this project I utilize Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering to detect and identify faulty sensors on centrifugal compressor.

Problem Overview
In our production units sensors have critical importance, and there are thousands of them. Just one faulty sensor may cause production losses that would yield negative millions of dollars. To prevent that and to be able to detect faulty instruments rapidly I created a tools that utilizes agglomorative hierarchical clustering to cluster similiar sensors with each other and detect faulty ones.

How does it work?
Application takes last 24 hours of data and assumes that all sensor are fine at the start and clusters data based on hierarchical clustring. We call those first clusters as finger-print of the unit. After every 8 hours (each one represent one shift) we take newly generated data and we cluster it to compare with finger print to detect any faulty sensor. IF all clusters are the same there is nothing to worry about. If each shifts data is O.K. then application uses newly generated 24 hours of data to produce new finger-print then uses to it to check future data. But if it finds any differences between finger-print clusters and newly generated clusters, application detects and identifies which sensor or sensors are clustered differently.

Metrics that I used
Since we don't have labeled data, Silhouette Coefficient calculated for every linkage method to find best performing method. After that visual checks conducted to see whether faults are detected or not.

Additional information about compressor.
Compressor has 41 sensors on it.

20 of them are tempreture sensors. (177TI2041A.PV, 177TI2041B.PV, 177TI2043A.PV, 177TI2045A.PV, 177TI2045B.PV, 177TI2048A.PV, 177TI2048B.PV, 177TI2048C.PV, 177TI2050A.PV, 177TI2051A.PV, 177TI2052A.PV, 177TI2056.PV, 177TI2057.PV, 177TI2053A.PV, 177TI2054A.PV, 177TI2055A.PV, 177TI2040B.PV, 177TI2040A.PV, 177TI2039A.PV, 177TI2039B.PV)

19 of them are vibration sensors. (177VI2041X.PV, 177VI2040Y.PV, 177VI2038Z.PV, 177VI2039Z.PV, 177VI2035.PV, 177VI2036.PV, 177VI2034X.PV, 177VI2033Y.PV, 177ZI2017A.PV, 177ZI2017B.PV, 177ZI2017C.PV, 177VI2013X.PV, 177VI2013Y.PV, 177VI2009X.PV, 177VI2009Y.PV, 177VI2005X.PV, 177VI2005Y.PV, 177VI2011Y.PV, 177VI2011X.PV)

One of them is electric motor rotation sensor. (177KI2025.PV)

Last of them is compressor rotation sensor. (177KI2030.PV)

In [25]:
#This function returns average silhouette score for given dataframe list.
def return_average_silhouette_score(clust, df_list):
    list_of_scores = []
    for df in df_list:
        labels = clust.fit_predict(df)
        score = metrics.silhouette_score(df, labels)
        list_of_scores.append(score)
        
    return sum(list_of_scores)/len(list_of_scores)
In [28]:
#instantiate HC clusters 
clust_single = cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='single')
clust_ward = cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='ward')
clust_average = cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='average')
clust_complete = cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='complete')
In [29]:
#Loop thru all in df_list_8hours to calculate silhouette coef. to compare which linkage method is better.
score_single = return_average_silhouette_score(clust_single, df_list_8Hours)
score_ward = return_average_silhouette_score(clust_ward, df_list_8Hours)
score_average = return_average_silhouette_score(clust_average, df_list_8Hours)
score_complete = return_average_silhouette_score(clust_single, df_list_8Hours)

print("Silhouette Coef for Single: {}\nSilhouette Coef for Ward: {}\nSilhouette Coef for Average: {}\n\
Silhouette Coef for Complete: {}\n".format(score_single,score_ward,score_average,score_complete))

CONCLUSION ON LINKAGE METHOD
¶

Each linkage method clusters our sensors correctly with similiar Silhouette Coefficient,
Decided to go with WARD linkage method.

#Start date  = (End Date) - (number_of_days)

#Fetches 24hours of data when its calld
fetcher_24hours = thd.ThdData(aggregateType='OPC_Time_Average'
                      ,interval='1min'
                      ,file_name='177K201_sensorNameList'
                      ,number_of_days=1)

#Fetches 8hours of data when its called
fetcher_8hours = thd.ThdData(aggregateType='OPC_Time_Average'
                      ,interval='1min'
                      ,file_name='177K201_sensorNameList'
                      ,number_of_days=1/3)
In [64]:
def main_app():
    #there are 3 shifts in one unit shift_counter represents that
    shift_counter=0 
    #is firts shift same as finger print
    is_first_ok=False
    #is second shift same as finger print
    is_second_ok=False
    #is third shift same as finger print
    is_third_ok=False
    
    while True:
        now = date.today()
        print('FETCHING DAILY DATA.. {}'.format(now))
        #Get daily data
        df_day = fetcher_24hours.download()
        #Preprocess
        #Returns Normalized Data.
        df_scaled = SFD.scalesData(df_day, is_normalize=True)

        #Transpose (We need to split the data so n=1)
        df_T = SFD.splitsTransposeData(df_scaled, n=1)[0]
        
        #Noise filtering DBSCAN
        df_f_T = SFD.filterDBSCAN(df_T)
        
        #instantiate Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustring instance
        clust = cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='complete')

        #Get fingerprint
        finger_print_df = df_f_T
        finger_print = SFD.returnSensorClusters(df=finger_print_df,clust=clust)

        while True:
            if (shift_counter == 0 or 1 or 2):        
                #Wait for 8 hours after that get new data and compare it with finger print
                time.sleep(60*60*8) #8hours
                #Get system date
                now_shift = datetime.now()
                #Format datetime
                dt_shift = now_shift.strftime("%d/%m/%Y %H:%M:%S")
                
                print('{} FETCHING SHIFT DATA.. {}'.format((shift_counter + 1), dt_shift))
                
                #Get data, normalize it, and transpose
                shift_df = SFD.splitsTransposeData(SFD.scalesData(fetcher_8hours.download(),is_normalize=True), n=1)[0]
                
                #Noise filter DBSCAN
                shift_df_f = SFD.filterDBSCAN(shift_df)
                
                #Get clusters for that shift        
                shift_state = SFD.returnSensorClusters(df=shift_df_f,clust=clust)

                #Check wheter or not finger print and shift state are the same
                if ((finger_print.equals(shift_state))):
                    if (shift_counter == 0):
                        print("first shift is ok")
                        is_first_ok = True
                        #shift is complete add one more    
                        shift_counter += 1
                    elif (shift_counter == 1):
                        print("second shift is ok")
                        is_second_ok = True
                        #shift is complete add one more    
                        shift_counter += 1
                    elif (shift_counter == 2):
                        print("third shift is ok")
                        is_third_ok = True
                        #shift is complete add one more    
                        shift_counter += 1
                else:
                    #print faulty sensors.
                    print("FAULT DETECTED.\nFAULTY SENSORS = {}".format(SFD.returnDifferentClusteredTags(finger_print, 
                                                                                                     shift_state)))
                    
                    #plot for compare two dataframe
                    SFD.plotComparisionPlot2(finger_print_df, shift_df)
                    
                    #Dont break the loop and change the finger_print.
                    #Because there is something wrong in the unit
                    #Dont update finger-print until unit comes back to normal.
                    is_first_ok = False
                    is_second_ok = False
                    is_third_ok = False
                    shift_counter = 0
     

                #If all 3 shift (1 day) is complete and if we dont detect fault we should use these new 24 hours data to
                #produce new finger print and repeat the same producure.
                if ((shift_counter == 3) and (is_first_ok==True) and (is_second_ok==True) and (is_third_ok==True)):
                    #ALL OK, Reset everthing.
                    print('All OK. Updating Finger-Print..')
                    shift_counter = 0
                    is_first_ok = False
                    is_second_ok = False
                    is_third_ok = False
                    break

Normaly program runs every 8 hours but for demo purposes, it runs every minute.

Further Improvements¶

Additional solutions¶

To improve existing solution and detect all faults another clustering algorithm might be used to cooperate with existing solution. For example DBSCAN might be good chooice to detect short lived faults.

Improvements for current solution¶

Another improvement can be made on top of existing solution might be predicting sensor readings while they are faulty.</br> For that reason neural networks solutions can be used.
